	<dd><a name="comment_841" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Michael</strong> replies:</em> monkeynuts on 15th Apr 2005 wrote:<br />"yeah yeah, participative democracy is a fine idea in theory, but it's ridiculously impractical.<br />I'm all in favour of increasing participation in the democratic process, but there simply aren't enough people with enough time, education or inclination to make properly informed decisions on executive policy."</p> <p>The reforms which we propose would give the electorate an option to put some bit of  "executive policy"   up for public debate, detailed scrutiny and if necessary referendum. What you call "ridiculously impractical", for instance citizens' initiative, selective veto of gov. bills, recall of elected persons, have already been up and running for many years in countries similar to ours.</p> <p>See arguments http://www.iniref.org/case.html<br />and proposals, resources http://www.iniref.org/index.html</p>
